<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 1) This camp can be &quot;claimed.&quot; That is to say, one force given rights to first kill attempt and thereby, rights to the loot if successful. But it order for it to be claimed, the cleric must have a killing force present during the camp. If the force dwindles, the cleric will be given a brief period to replenish the force by whatever means within their sphere of influence. If the force cannot be replenished or the cleric leaves the zone for a reasonable amount of time, the claim is lost.<br>
<br>
2) A single cleric at the camp has no legitimate claim rights as described in #1.<br>
<br>
3) If multiple single clerics are contending for the camp and Ragefire spawns, whichever one who engages Ragefire with killing force first has rights to the kill. (This is effectively a race to get your people in the zone, to the spawn.)<br>
<br>
4) Kiting does not count as killing force engagement and thus gives no right to the kill.<br>
<br>
5) If one force fails* their attempt, they lose their claim and any killing force standing by is entitled to attempt the kill. If multiple killing forces are standing by, it would be FCFS.<br>
<br>
<br>
Those are the rules the GM's consider when making an arbitration about contention in this spawn. <br>
<br>
The Server GM said he and other server GM's are trying to get this quest changed yet again because of the contention problems. <br>
<br>
---------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Q) In GM # 5, if the first attempt fails, but no one else engages the mob while the first triggering group recovers, can the first group re-engage when ready or do they have to wait on anyone else who wants to take a turn before taking another shot?<br>
<br>
A.) If the first force is recooperated, ready, and able to kill and the second one is not completely or very nearly ready (like 5-10 mins from away from readiness) then yes, they may go again. If the second force is completely ready and able to kill (in which case they probably would have immediately engaged it upon the disengagement of the first force), then no, the first force must wait their turn (and they probably won't get one, but you never know).<br>
<br>
Q.) What is &quot;fail&quot;? Is it merely the reduction of your killing force to the point that the kill is not possibile (only feigners or offline rezzers left alive, no one dealing damage)? Does &quot;failure&quot; only come when the attackers cry &quot;Uncle&quot; and leave?&lt;&lt;<br>
<br>
A.) It would be the first case. Failure means the mob is disengaged. For example, if all that's left is feigners, camped out clerics, and a bard or druid kiting around Ragefire (remember kiting does not count as engagement) til the force can recoop, they have failed and their turn is over.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Naele Shadowslayer<br>
Affliction<br>
